SIMPLE: inarticulate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inarticulate
<hw>In`ar*tic"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inarticulatus</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> not +
<ets>articulatus</ets> articulate.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not uttered with articulation or intelligible
distinctness, as speech or words.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Music which is <qex>inarticulate</qex> poesy.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Not jointed or
articulated; having no distinct body segments; <as>as, an
<ex>inarticulate</ex> worm</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Without a
hinge; -- said of an order (<spn>Inarticulata</spn> or
<spn>Ecardines</spn>) of brachiopods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Incapable of articulating.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The poor earl, who is <qex>inarticulate</qex> with palsy.</q>
<rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Incapable of expressing one's ideas or feelings
clearly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inarticulated</ent>⟦br⟧
